Jesus turned and saw her. He said to her, "Woman, do not lose hope." "Your faith has healed you." The woman was healed at that moment.
When Jesus entered the governor's house, he saw the flute players there. And he saw the noisy crowds.
He said, "Go. The girl is not dead. She is sleeping." But they laughed at him.
After the crowd had left, Jesus entered. He took the girl by the hand, and she arose.
News about all that Jesus did spread throughout that region. Jesus heals two blind men.
As Jesus went on from there, two blind men followed him, calling out, "Have mercy on us, Son of David!"
When Jesus entered the house, the blind men came to him. He asked them, "Do you believe that I can do this?" They answered, "Yes, Lord."
Then he touched their eyes and said, "According to your faith let it be done to you."
Now they could see again. And Jesus sternly warned them: "See that no one knows about this."
But they went out and spread the news. They talked about it everywhere in that area.
As they were leaving, another man who was demon-possessed was brought to Jesus. He was unable to speak.
When the demon was cast out, the man spoke. The crowds were amazed. They said, "Never has anything like this been seen in Israel."
But the Pharisees said, "He casts out demons by the prince of the demons." Few are the workers.
Jesus went through all the towns and villages, teaching in their synagogues, preaching the good news of the Kingdom of God, and healing every disease and sickness.
When he saw the crowds, he felt deep compassion for them. They were harassed and helpless, like sheep without a shepherd.
Then Jesus said to his disciples, "The harvest is plentiful, but the laborers are few."
Therefore pray the Lord of the harvest to send out laborers into his harvest.
Jesus sends the twelve disciples.
Jesus called his twelve disciples to him and gave them authority to drive out impure spirits and to heal every disease and every sickness.
Here are the names of the twelve apostles. First comes Simon Peter and his brother Andrew. Then comes James, the son of Zebedee, and his brother John.
Then come Philip and Bartholomew, as well as Thomas and Matthew the tax collector. There are also James the son of Alphaeus and Thaddaeus.
The last two are Simon the Zealot and Judas Iscariot. Judas is the one who would later betray Jesus to his enemies.
Jesus sent out the twelve with these instructions: "Do not go to the Gentiles," he said, "and do not enter any town of the Samaritans."
Instead, go to the Children of Israel. They are like lost sheep.
As you go, preach this message: 'The kingdom of heaven is near.'
Heal the sick. Raise the dead. Cleanse the lepers. Cast out demons. Freely you have received, freely give.
Do not carry gold, or silver, or copper in your belts.
Don't take a bag on the trip. Don't take extra clothes, sandals, or a walking stick. The worker should be given what he needs.
When you enter a town or village, look for someone willing to accommodate you. Stay with this person until you leave.
When you enter the house, greet those inside.
If that house welcomes you, give it your peace. If not, do not bless it.
Some people may not welcome you or listen to your words. If they don't, shake the dust off your feet when you leave that house or town.
What I am determined to say is true. On the day of judgment, it will be easier for Sodom and Gomorrah than for that city.
I send you out as sheep among wolves. Therefore be wise as serpents and innocent as doves.
Beware! People will hand you over to the local courts. They will flog you in their assemblies.
You will be brought before rulers and kings because of me, and you will be witnesses to them and to the Gentiles.
But when they arrest you, do not worry about what to say or how to say it. At that time, the right words will be given to you.
You will not be the speaker. It is the Spirit of your Father who will speak through you.
Brothers will deliver up brothers to death, and fathers their children, and children will rise up against parents and cause them to die.
Everyone will hate you because of me. But those who endure to the end will be saved.
When people attack you in one place, flee to another. What I am about to tell you is the truth. You will not finish going through the cities of Israel before the Son of Man comes.
A student is not better than his teacher. Nor is a servant better than his master.
It is enough for the disciple to be like his teacher, and enough for the servant to be like his master. If the master of the house is called Beelzebul, what will they say of the rest of his household?
Therefore do not fear them. For there is nothing covered that will not be revealed, and hidden that will not be known.
What is whispered in your ear, proclaim from the rooftops.
Do not fear those who kill the body but cannot kill the soul. Rather, fear him who can destroy both soul and body in hell.
Are not two sparrows sold for a penny? Yet not one of them will fall to the ground apart from your Father's will.
He even counts every hair on your head!
So do not fear, for you are worth more than many sparrows.
What if someone says in front of others that he knows me? I too will say in front of my Father in heaven that I know him.
But what about someone who says in front of others that he doesn't know me? I will say in front of my Father in heaven that I don't know him.
Do not think that I have come to bring peace to the earth. I have not come to bring peace, but a sword.
I have come to set a son against his father, a daughter against her mother, and a daughter-in-law against her mother-in-law.
A man's enemies are the men of his own house. (Micah 7:6)
Whoever loves his father or mother more than me is not worthy of me. And whoever loves his son or daughter more than me is not worthy of me.
And whoever does not take up their cross and follow me is not worthy of me.
"Whoever finds their life will lose it, and whoever loses their life for my sake will find it."
Whoever welcomes you welcomes me, and whoever welcomes me welcomes the one who sent me.
If anyone welcomes a prophet as a prophet, they will receive the reward of a prophet. And if anyone welcomes a righteous person as righteous, they will receive the reward of a righteous person.
"Truly I tell you, anyone who gives you a cup of cold water to drink because you are my disciple, will by no means lose their reward."
Jesus and John the Baptist
Jesus finished teaching his twelve disciples. Then he set out to teach and preach in the towns of Galilee.
John was in prison. When he heard what Jesus was doing, he sent his disciples to him.
They asked Jesus, "Are you the one who is to come, or should we expect another?"
Jesus answered, "Go and tell John what you hear and see."
The blind receive their sight. The lame walk. Those with leprosy are cleansed. The deaf hear. The dead are raised to life. And the good news is preached to the poor.
"Blessed are those who did not abandon their faith because of me."
As John's disciples were leaving, Jesus began to speak to the crowds about John. He said, "What did you go out into the wilderness to see? A reed swayed by the wind?"
If not, what did you go out to see? A man clothed in fine garments? No. Those who wear fine garments are in the palaces of kings.
"What did you go out to see? A prophet? Yes, I tell you, and more than a prophet."
He is the one who was written about in the book. It says, " 'I will send my messenger ahead of you to prepare your way' (Malachi 3:1)."
What I am about to tell you is the truth. No one greater than John the Baptist has ever been born, but the least in the kingdom of heaven is greater than he.
From the days of John the Baptist until now, the kingdom of heaven has been forcefully advancing, and forceful people lay hold of it.
All the prophets and the law prophesied until John came.
If you are willing to accept it, John is the Elijah who was to come.
"He who has an ear, let him hear."
What shall I compare the people of today to? They are like children sitting in the marketplaces, calling out. They say:
We played the flute for you, but you did not dance. We sang a funeral song, but you did not mourn.
When John came, he neither ate nor drank as you eat and drink, and people say, "He is possessed by a demon."
But when the Son of Man came, he ate and drank, and they say, 'Look at this glutton and drunkard, a friend of tax collectors and sinners!' Those who act wisely prove that their wisdom is good. Cities that do not repent of sin.
Jesus began to denounce the cities where most of his miracles had been done, because they did not repent of their sins. He said:
Woe to you, Korazin! Woe to you, Bethsaida! For if the miracles that were performed in you had been performed in Tyre and Sidon, they would have repented long ago, sitting in sackcloth and ashes.
But I tell you, on the day of judgment it will be more tolerable for Tyre and Sidon than for you.
And you, Capernaum, will you be exalted to heaven? No, you will be brought down to Hades. For if the miracles had been done in Sodom which were done in you, it would have remained until this day.
But I say to you, it will be more bearable for Sodom on the day of judgment than for you. Come to me, all who are weary and burdened, and I will give you rest.
At that time Jesus said, "I thank you, Father, Lord of heaven and earth, because you have hidden these things from the wise and intelligent and have revealed them to infants."
Yes, Father. This is what you wanted.
My father gave me everything. The Father is the only one who knows the Son. And the only ones who know the Father are the Son and those the Son chooses to make known to them.
Come to me, all you who are weary and burdened, and I will give you rest.
"Be my disciples and learn from me. I am meek and lowly in heart, and you will find rest for your souls."
"My service is easy, and my burden is light."
Jesus is Lord of the Sabbath.
On a Sabbath day, Jesus was going through the grainfields. His disciples were hungry, so they began to pick and eat some of the grain.
The Pharisees saw this and said to Jesus, "Look! It is against the law to do this on the Sabbath. Yet your disciples are doing it!"
Jesus answered, "Have you not read what David did when he was hungry, and those who were with him?"
Then he entered the house of God, and he and his men ate the sacred bread, which was not permitted except for the priests.
Haven't you read the Law? It tells how the priests in the Temple are to perform their duties every Sabbath day. Yet they are not considered guilty.
I tell you, something greater than the temple is here.
The scriptures say, "I desire mercy, not sacrifice." (Hosea 6:6) You do not know the meaning of these words. If you did, you would not file lawsuits against the innocent.
"The Son of Man is Lord of the Sabbath."
Then Jesus went from there and entered their synagogue.
There was a man with a withered and paralyzed hand. The Pharisees were trying to find fault with Jesus. They asked him, "Is it lawful to heal on the Sabbath?"
He said to them, "If one of your sheep falls into a pit on the Sabbath, will you not take hold of it and lift it out?"
Man is more valuable than sheep! That is why the law allows us to do good on the Sabbath.
Then Jesus said to the man, "Stretch out your hand." He stretched it out, and it was restored, just like the other one.
But the Pharisees went out and conspired against Jesus, the chosen servant of God, to kill him.
Jesus knew of the Pharisees' plots. So he left that place. Many followed him, and he healed all their sick.
But he warned them not to tell anyone about his identity.
That was to fulfill what was spoken by the prophet Isaiah, saying,
Here is my servant, whom I have chosen. He is the one I love; I am pleased with him. I will put my Spirit on him, and he will proclaim justice to the nations.
He will not argue or shout. No one will hear his voice in the streets.
It will not break a bent branch. It will not extinguish a flickering flame. It will fix everything.
"The nations will put their hope in him." (Isaiah 42:1-4) Jesus and Beelzebul
A man possessed by demons, who was blind and could not speak, was brought to Jesus. Jesus healed him, and the man was able to speak and see.
All the people were amazed and said, "Could this be the Son of David?"
When the Pharisees heard this, they said, "This man drives out demons only by Beelzebul, the ruler of the demons."
Jesus knew their thoughts and said to them, "Every kingdom divided against itself is brought to desolation. And every city or house divided against itself will not stand."
"The devil drives out the devil, so he wages war against himself. How then can his kingdom stand?"
"You say that I cast out demons by the power of Beelzebul. But by whose power do your disciples cast them out? Therefore, they will be your judges."
But if I cast out demons by the Spirit of God, then the kingdom of God has come to you.
Or think about this. How can you enter the house of a strong man and simply take what he has? You must first bind him. Then you can rob his house.
He who is not with me is against me, and he who does not gather with me scatters.
And this is what I say to you: Every sin and every evil word spoken against God will be forgiven. But speaking evil against the Holy Spirit will not be forgiven.
Whoever speaks a word against the Son of Man will be forgiven, but whoever speaks against the Holy Spirit will not be forgiven. This person will not be forgiven, either in this world or in the world to come.
A good tree bears good fruit, and a bad tree bears bad fruit. You can tell a tree by its fruit.
"A brood of vipers! How can you who are evil say anything good? For out of the abundance of the heart the mouth speaks."
A good man says good things. They spring from the good within him. And an evil man says evil things. They spring from the evil within him.
But I tell you that everyone will have to give account on the day of judgment for every empty word they have spoken.
"By your words you will be justified, and by your words you will be condemned." The miracle of Jonah.
Some Pharisees and scribes came to Jesus and said, "Teacher, we wish to see a sign from you."
He answered, "An evil and adulterous generation seeks a sign, but no sign will be given to it except the sign of the prophet Jonah."
"Jonah was in the belly of a great fish for three days and three nights. Something similar will happen to the Son of Man. He will be in the tomb for three days and three nights."
The men of Nineveh will rise up at the judgment with this generation and condemn it; for they repented at the preaching of Jonah, and behold, something greater than Jonah is here.
The queen of the south will rise up in the judgment with this generation, and will condemn them: for she came from the uttermost parts of the earth to hear the wisdom of Solomon; and behold, there is one here greater than Solomon.
What happens when an evil spirit departs from a human? It wanders through desolate places seeking a resting place, but finds none.
Then he says, "I will return to my house that I left." When he arrived there, he found the house empty. The house had been swept and organized.
Then the unclean spirit goes out of the man, and takes with him seven other spirits more wicked than himself. They enter and dwell there, and the last state of that man becomes worse than the first. Even so shall it be also unto this wicked generation. - Mother and brothers of Jesus
While Jesus was still speaking to the crowds, his mother and brothers were standing outside, wanting to speak to him.
Someone told him, "Your mother and brothers are standing outside. They want to speak to you."
Jesus answered and said to him, "Who is my mother? And who are my brothers?"
Jesus pointed to his disciples. He said, "Behold, my mother! Behold, my brothers!"
"Whoever does the will of my Father in heaven is my brother and sister and mother."
The Farmer's Tale
On that very day, Jesus went out from the house and sat by the Sea of Galilee.
A large crowd gathered around him. He got into a boat, sat in it, and all the people stood on the shore.
Then he told them many stories. He said, "A farmer went out to sow his seed.
He scattered the seeds on the ground. Some fell on the path. Birds came and ate them.
Some seeds fell on rocky places, where there was not much soil. The plants grew quickly, because the soil was not deep.
When the sun rose, it scorched the plants. They withered because they had no roots.
Other seeds fell among the thorns. The thorns grew up and choked the plants.
And some seeds fell on good soil, and produced a crop, a hundred, or sixty, or thirty times what was sown.
"He who has an ear, let him hear."
The disciples came to him. They asked, "Why do you speak to the people in parables?"
He answered, "To you it has been given to know the secrets of the kingdom of heaven, but to them it has not been given."
Whoever has this kind of knowledge will be given more. Indeed, he will have abundance. But whoever does not have this kind of knowledge, even what he has will be taken away from him.
Here's the reason I resort to stories when I talk to people. I say, "They look, but they don't really see. They listen, but they don't really hear or understand."
In them is fulfilled the prophecy of Isaiah: "You will indeed hear, but never understand; you will indeed see, but never perceive."
"Their hearts are calloused; they cannot hear with their ears. They have closed their eyes, so that they cannot see with their eyes, nor hear with their ears, nor understand with their hearts, nor turn back to the Lord and be healed." (Isaiah 6:9-10)
But blessed are your eyes, for they see; and blessed are your ears, for they hear.
What I am determined to tell you is true. Many prophets and righteous people wanted to see what you see, but they did not see it. They wanted to hear what you hear, but they did not hear it.
Listen! Here is the meaning of the farmer's story.
People hear the message of the kingdom but do not understand it. Then the evil one comes and steals what was sown in their hearts. Those people are like the seed sown on the path.
Others received the seed that fell on rocky ground. These are the ones who hear the word and receive it with joy at once.
But they have no root; they last only for a short time. When trouble or persecution comes because of the word, they quickly fall away.
And others fell among thorns. These are the ones who, when they hear the word, immediately receive it with joy. But they have no root in themselves, and only endure for a while. For when tribulation or persecution arises because of the word, immediately they stumble.
But others received the seed that fell on good soil. These are the ones who hear the word and understand it. They produce a crop, yielding a hundred, sixty, or thirty times what was sown. The Parable of the Sower and the Soils.
Jesus told the crowds another story. "This is how the kingdom of heaven is," he said. "A man planted good seed in his field."
But while everyone was sleeping, his enemy came. The enemy planted weeds among the wheat and then left.
The wheat began to grow and form grains. At the same time, weeds appeared.
The servants of the master came and said, "Master, did you not sow good seed in your field? How then does it have tares?"
He said, "An enemy did this." The servants asked, "Do you want us to go and pull the weeds?"
"No," the owner replied. "While you're weeding, you might pull up the wheat along with the weeds."
Let both grow together until the harvest. Then I will tell the workers what to do. This is what I will say to them: "First, gather the weeds. Bind them in bundles to be burned. Then gather the wheat. Bring it into my barn." Parables about the mustard seed and the leaven.
Jesus told the crowds another parable. He said, "The kingdom of heaven is like a mustard seed. A man took the seed and planted it in his field."
It is the smallest of all your seeds. Yet when it grows, it is the largest of all the plants in the garden. It becomes a tree. And the birds come and rest in its branches.
Jesus told them another parable: "The kingdom of heaven is like yeast that a woman took and mixed into three measures of flour until all the dough had risen."
Jesus spoke all these things to the crowds in parables. He did not say anything to them without using a parable.
Thus were fulfilled the words which the prophet spoke, saying, "I will open my mouth in parables; I will utter hidden things from the foundation of the world." (Psalm 78:2) Jesus explains the parable of the tares.
Then Jesus left the crowds and went into the house. And his disciples came to him and said, "Explain to us the parable of the weeds in the field."
He answered and said, "He that soweth the good seed is the Son of man."
The field is the world. The good seed are those who belong to the kingdom of God. The tares are those who belong to the evil one.
The enemy who sows it is the devil. The harvest is the day of judgment. And the workers are angels.
Weeds are pulled up and burned in the fire. That is how it will be on the Day of Judgment.
The Son of Man will send his angels, and they will remove from his kingdom everything that causes sin and all who do evil.
They will cast them into the fiery furnace. There they will weep and gnash their teeth.
Then the people of God will shine like the sun in their Father's kingdom. He who has ears, let him hear. Parables of the hidden treasure and the pearl.
The kingdom of heaven is like a treasure hidden in a field. When a man found it, he hid it again, and then in his joy went and sold all he had and bought that field.
And again, the kingdom of heaven is like a merchant in search of fine pearls.
He found one that was very precious. So he went and sold all he had. And he bought that pearl. The parable of the net.
And again, the kingdom of heaven is like a net that was thrown into the sea, and gathered every kind of fish.
When it was full, the fishermen pulled it to shore. Then they sat down and gathered the good fish into baskets. But they threw away the bad fish.
This will be the case on the Day of Judgment. The angels will come. They will separate those who did evil from those who did good.
The wicked will be thrown into the blazing furnace. There will be weeping and gnashing of teeth.
"Do you understand all these things?" asked Jesus. "Yes," they answered.
He said to them, "Every scribe who has been trained for the kingdom of heaven is like the master of a household who brings out of his treasure what is new and what is old." A prophet without honor.
Jesus finished telling these stories. Then he left.
He came to his hometown, Nazareth. There he began to teach the people in their synagogue, and they were amazed. They said, "Where did this man get this wisdom? And where does he have the power to do miracles?"
Isn't this the carpenter's son? Isn't his mother's name Mary? Aren't his brothers James and Joseph and Simon and Judas?
Aren't all his sisters with us? So where did this man get all these things?
They never liked him. But Jesus said to them, "A prophet is not without honor except in his own town, and among his relatives and in his own home."
He performed few miracles there because they had little faith.
John the Baptist's head is cut off.
At that time Herod the tetrarch heard the reports about Jesus.
He said to his servants, "This is John the Baptist. He has risen from the dead! That is why he has the power to do miracles."
Herod arrested John. He bound him and put him in prison because of Herodias, who was the wife of Philip, Herod's brother.
John said to Herod, "It is not lawful for you to have her."
Herod wanted to kill John. But he feared the people, for they believed John to be a prophet.
On Herod's birthday, Herodias' daughter danced for him and his guests. He was delighted with her.
He promised her by oath to give her what she asked for.
Her mother told her what to say. So the girl said to Herod, "Give me the head of John the Baptist on a platter."
The king was very annoyed. However, he remembered his promise and his dinner guests. So, he ordered one of his men to give her what she asked for.
Herod ordered John's head to be cut off in prison.
His head was brought on a large platter and given to the maid. She then carried it to her mother.
John's disciples came and took his body and buried it. Then they went and told Jesus. Jesus feeds five thousand people.
When Jesus heard what had happened to John, he withdrew to a solitary place by boat. But when the crowds heard it, they followed him on foot from the towns.
When Jesus landed on the shore, he saw a large crowd. He felt deep compassion for them. He healed their sick.
When evening came, the disciples approached him and said, "There is nothing here but a boy with five barley loaves and two fish." "Send the crowd away," Jesus replied, "so they can go to the villages and buy food for themselves."
Jesus answered, "They need not depart; give ye them to eat."
"We have only five loaves of bread and two fish," they answered.
He said, "Bring them to me."
Then Jesus commanded the people to sit down on the grass. He took the five loaves and the two fish, and looking up to heaven, he gave thanks. He broke the loaves and gave them to the disciples, and the disciples gave them to the people.
They all ate and were satisfied. The disciples picked up twelve baskets of the fragments.
The number of men who ate was about 5000. Women and children also ate. Jesus walks on water.
So Jesus immediately made the disciples get into the boat and go before him to the other side, while he dismissed the crowds.
After sending them away, he went up on the mountain by himself to pray. When evening came, he was there alone.
The boat had already moved away from the shore. The waves were hitting it hard because the wind was blowing against it.
Early in the morning, Jesus came to the disciples. He walked on the lake.
They saw him walking on the lake and were terrified. They said, "It's a ghost!" and cried out in fear.
Jesus immediately called out to them: "Take courage! It is I. Do not be afraid."
"Lord, are you?" Peter asked. "If it is you, command me to come to you on the water."
Jesus said, "Come." So Peter got out of the boat and walked on the water toward Jesus.
But when Peter saw the wind, he was afraid. He began to sink. He cried out, "Lord, save me!"
Then Jesus reached out his hand and touched him. "Your faith is small," he said, "Why did you doubt me?"
When they boarded the boat, the wind died down.
Then those who were in the boat worshiped Jesus, saying, "Truly you are the Son of God!"
And they came over unto the other side of the sea, into the country of the Gerasenes.
The men who lived there recognized Jesus. They sent word throughout all the surrounding countryside. People brought all their sick to Jesus.
They pleaded with him to allow those who were sick to touch the hem of his garment, and everyone who touched it was healed.
What makes people "unclean"?
Some Pharisees and teachers of the law came from Jerusalem to see Jesus. They asked:
Why don't your students obey what the elders teach? Your students don't wash their hands before eating!
Jesus answered, "Why do you not obey the command of God, but prefer to follow your own teachings?"
God said, "Honor your father and your mother" (Exodus 20:12; Deuteronomy 5:16) and also, "Whoever curses his father or his mother shall be put to death" (Exodus 21:17; Leviticus 20:9).
But you teach them to say to their parents, "Any help anyone of us gives you is a gift dedicated to God."
Therefore they need not honor their parents with their gift. You nullify the word of God by your tradition.
Protesters! Isaiah was right when he prophesied about you. He said:
"These people honor me with their words, but their hearts are far from me."
"Their worship means nothing to me. They only know one thing: human laws." (Isaiah 29:13)
Jesus called the crowd to Him and said, "Listen and understand."
What goes into your mouth does not defile you; what comes out of your mouth, that is what defiles you.
Then his disciples came to him and asked, "Do you know that the Pharisees were offended when they heard this?"
Jesus answered them, "There are some among you who do not belong to God. Therefore, they cannot be from God's family."
Leave them. The Pharisees are blind guides. If the blind lead the blind, both will fall into a pit.
Peter said, "Explain this to us."
"Do you not yet understand?" Jesus asked them.
Don't you see? Everything that goes into the mouth goes to the stomach. Then it comes out of the body.
But the things that come out of the mouth come from the heart. These are the things that make you "unclean."
Evil thoughts come from the heart. So do murder, adultery, and other lusts. So do theft, bearing false witness, and slandering others.
These are the things that make you "unclean." But eating without washing your hands doesn't make you "unclean." "The faith of a Canaanite woman"
Jesus left Galilee and went to the region of Tyre and Sidon.
There was a Canaanite woman who lived near the cities of Tyre and Sidon. She came to him and cried out, "Lord, Son of David, have mercy on me! My daughter is tormented by a demon. She suffers greatly."
Jesus said not a word. His disciples came to him and pleaded with him, "Send her away, for she keeps crying out after us."
Jesus answered, "I was sent only to the lost sheep of the house of Israel."
Then the woman knelt before him. "Oh God! Save me!" she said.
He answered and said, "It is not meet to take the children's bread, and cast it to dogs."
"Yes, Lord," she said. "Even the dogs eat the crumbs that fall from their masters' table."
Then Jesus answered and said to her, "O woman, great is your faith! Let it be to you as you desire." And her daughter was healed from that very hour. Jesus feeds four thousand.
Jesus departed from there and walked along the Sea of Galilee. Then he went up into the hills and sat down.
A large crowd came to him, bringing with them the blind, the lame, the paralyzed, the mute, and many others. They placed them at his feet, and he healed them.
People were amazed. Those who could not speak were speaking. The weak were healed. The lame were walking. The blind were seeing. So the people praised the God of Israel.
Then Jesus called his disciples to him and said, "I have great compassion on this crowd. They have been with me for three days now and have nothing to eat. I do not want to send them away hungry, or they may collapse on the way."
His disciples answered, "There is nothing here but five loaves and two fish." "How far away from a town are we?" they asked Jesus.
"How many loaves do you have?" asked Jesus. "Seven," they answered, "and a few small fish."
Jesus told the crowd to sit down on the ground.
He took the seven loaves and the fish and gave thanks. Then he broke them and gave them to the disciples, and the disciples distributed them to the people.
They all ate and were satisfied. The disciples picked up seven baskets of the leftover fragments.
The number of men who ate was 4000. Women and children also ate.
After Jesus had dismissed the crowds, he got into the boat and went to the region of Magadan.
Jesus is asked for a sign or miracle.
The Pharisees and Sadducees came to test Jesus, and asked him to show them a sign from heaven.
He replied: "In the evening you look at the sky. You say: 'The weather will be good. The sky is red.'"
